#####
Tilde (~) expression within the shell is useful when writing scripts that need to work across  multiple directories.


It is performed using special character named tilda(~)
tilda (~) using refers to the home directory
echo ~
echo ~tushendra(name of the user present) -- it will refer to the home directory of the user
echo ~root
note: only if user is present then it will refer to home directory of user

PWD: Print Working Directory
we can use following tilda(~) expression to represent
 1= ~+  -- to represent the PWD
 2= ~-  -- to represent the Old PWD variable
